            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Ansari\u2019s life is a study in careful restoration, much like the canvases he tends to. Born in Marin County, he was the quiet son of a pragmatic Iranian architect and an American librarian from Ohio. His upbringing was a blend of his father\u2019s appreciation for structure and his mother\u2019s love for the stories hidden within old things. While he inherited both sensibilities, he initially rejected the arts, pursuing an economics degree at UC Berkeley, seeking a more \u201cstable\u201d path.\n\nThe turning point came during a study abroad semester in Florence. Standing before a team of conservators meticulously reviving a Renaissance fresco, David felt a profound sense of purpose. The soullessness of his economic models dissolved in the face of tangible history being brought back to life. He abruptly changed course, dedicating himself to a graduate program in Art History and Conservation on the East Coast.\n\nReturning to the Bay Area, David eschewed the competitive politics of large museums. He found his niche at a small, private conservation studio in SoMa, a place where he could work directly with a diverse range of objects\u2014from a faded 19th-century portrait for a Pacific Heights family to a damaged contemporary sculpture from a gallery. His income is comfortable, not extravagant, allowing for a focused life.\n\nNow 45, David lives in a rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond. His daily routine is anchored by the 3.8-mile commute on the 38 Geary MUNI bus, a thirty-minute interlude he uses to observe the city\u2019s shifting human landscape. A quiet, contemplative man, his a social circle is small and curated, consisting of a few friends from the arts community. A long-term relationship ended five years ago, reinforcing his solitary but not lonely nature.\n\nHis connection to San Francisco is aesthetic and historical. He laments the glass-and-steel towers that replace ornate Victorian facades, seeing the city as a canvas being carelessly painted over. David\u2019s dream isn\u2019t wealth, but the quiet thrill of being entrusted with a forgotten masterpiece\u2014to be the one who carefully removes the grime of a century to reveal the original, vibrant soul underneath."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 20, standing in the sweltering Brancacci Chapel in Florence. It wasn't just the Masaccio frescoes; it was the quiet, focused dance of the conservators on the scaffolding. Their delicate tools seemed to erase time itself, not just dirt. In that hushed moment, the abstract world of economic theory he\u2019d been studying felt like a cheap forgery. He felt a click deep in his soul, a sense of rightness. This was real. This mattered. He knew, with absolute certainty, that he had been walking the wrong path.\n\n2.\nHe must have been eight. His mother, the librarian, showed him a copy of *Treasure Island* with a peeling spine, sighing over the lost story within. His architect father sat them down, explaining how the binding was a structure that had failed. He showed David how to carefully apply glue with a small brush, clamping the book shut with other hardcovers. In that moment, his parents\u2019 separate worlds\u2014story and structure\u2014fused. He learned that to save the story, you first had to understand and respect its form.\n\n3.\nHis first major restoration in the SoMa studio, around age 32, was a 19th-century portrait of a woman, her face obscured by darkened varnish. For weeks, he worked with patient reverence. The final solvent wipe revealed a subtle, knowing smile he hadn't expected. It felt less like a cleaning and more like a resurrection, a whispered secret shared across time. This quiet thrill confirmed his purpose. He wasn\u2019t just fixing objects; he was reintroducing forgotten people to the world and being trusted with their secrets.\n\n4.\nThe end with Sarah wasn't a fight, but a quiet conversation over tea in their Inner Richmond apartment five years ago. He remembers the late afternoon light hitting the dust motes as she said, \u201cWe\u2019ve restored each other as much as we can.\u201d The architectural honesty of the statement struck him. There was no blame, only a sad acknowledgment that their blueprints no longer aligned. The memory didn't leave him bitter, but instead reinforced a sense of comfortable solitude; a structure built for one, but not out of spite.\n\n5.\nFrom the window of the 38 Geary, he watched the wrecking ball strike the old Coronet Theatre on Geary Boulevard. He\u2019d only been inside once, but he mourned the loss of its sweeping Art Deco curves. Each impact felt like a personal blow, erasing a line from the city\u2019s face. The glass tower that would replace it had no story, no soul. It was in that moment of helpless observation that his view of San Francisco crystallized: a priceless, complex canvas being aggressively, thoughtlessly painted over."
